		<title type="html"><![CDATA[The World&#8217;s Greatest Burrito]]></title>
		<link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="http://www.roadtrip20.com/2007_12_07-the-worlds-greatest-burrito.html" />
		<id>http://www.roadtrip20.com/2007_12_07-the-worlds-greatest-burrito.html</id>
		<updated>2007-12-07T23:16:11Z</updated>
		<published>2007-12-07T23:16:11Z</published>
		<category scheme="http://www.roadtrip20.com" term="Pictures" /><category scheme="http://www.roadtrip20.com" term="Interesting Events" />		<summary type="html"><![CDATA[Anyone who knows me and my culinary preferences knows how much I love a good burrito.
Ben = Burrito lover.  Burrito lover = Ben.
How can you not love a burrito?  It&#8217;s a glorious configuration of nutrition (protein, carbs, and vegetables) and flavor (seasoned steak and hot sauce) all wrapped up in a neat, portable, [...]]]></summary>
		<content type="html" xml:base="http://www.roadtrip20.com/2007_12_07-the-worlds-greatest-burrito.html"><![CDATA[<p>Anyone who knows me and my culinary preferences knows how much I love a good burrito.</p>
<p>Ben = Burrito lover.  Burrito lover = Ben.</p>
<p>How can you not love a burrito?  It&#8217;s a glorious configuration of nutrition (protein, carbs, and vegetables) and flavor (seasoned steak and hot sauce) all wrapped up in a neat, portable, shiny package.  Anyone who argues against the deliciousness of a good burrito should check themselves into the looney bin.  Now.</p>
<p>Those who are familiar with my burrito-love have also likely heard me declare the supremacy of a Texas chain called: <a href="http://www.freebirds.com/">Freebirds</a>.  Until this trip, I had only eaten at Qdoba, Chipotle, Moe&#8217;s and other miscellaneous Mexican restaurants with less of a focus on the burrito.</p>
<p>After this trip, I&#8217;ve eaten burritos at about a dozen cities throughout the continent.  Aside from the <em>uniquely fantastic</em> burrito at &#8220;La Paz&#8221; in Los Angeles, my declaration of Freebirds having the world&#8217;s best burrito still stands.</p>
<p>To commemorate the verification of this declaration, I decided to celebrate.</p>
<p>I celebrated with what&#8217;s known as the &#8220;Super Monster.&#8221;  Other than places like Golden Corral, it&#8217;s the epitome of gluttony: Two 14&#8243; tortillas, end to end, in a massive 3+ pound structure and composition that&#8217;s larger than my face.</p>
<p>I prepared by eating 3 &#8220;Monster&#8221; burritos in 8 hours in Dallas, 3 days before.  To shove this thing down your gullet requires sincere and dedicated preparation fit for the Olympics.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/roadtrip20/2093495441/"><img src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2165/2093495441_898a990a7f_m.jpg" height="161" width="240" /></a></p>
<p>75% Done:</p>
<p><a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/roadtrip20/2093496179/"><img src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2054/2093496179_ac6e4e2ae2_m.jpg" height="161" width="240" /></a></p>
<p>As symbolically as man&#8217;s landing on the moon, I finished it.</p>
]]></content>
